# Git: commit and push every change batch

When you finish a coherent set of edits in this repository:

1. Run `git status` and ensure only intended files are staged.
2. `git add` the relevant paths (or `-A` when the whole change set should ship).
3. `git commit -m "..."` with a short, accurate message (present tense, what changed and why if non-obvious).
4. **Always push** so the remote stays in sync. In this repo local `main` tracks
   `origin/har-imu-labeled-stream` (different names), so plain `git push` may
   fail; use:
   `git push origin HEAD:har-imu-labeled-stream`
   until the default branch is renamed to match. If remotes or branch names change,
   use the equivalent explicit refspec or `git push -u origin <local>:<remote>`.
5. If push fails (auth, 403, publickey), report the error and the exact command to retry after the user fixes credentials; do not skip commit locally.

Do not leave local-only commits when the user expects GitHub to mirror the repo.
